## Chapter 3 — Image Processing in Traffic Management

Image processing enables the system to monitor and evaluate traffic patterns with high precision. By analyzing visual data, the system can:

- Detect the density of vehicles on specific lanes
- Identify congested areas in real time
- Measure vehicle speed and count vehicles
- Predict lane requirements based on traffic behavior

### 3.1 Components Used

- **Camera / Imaging Device** — Captures real-time images or video
- **Raspberry Pi** — Processes image data using Python libraries and ML models
- **OpenCV / TFLite Runtime** — Libraries for image processing and inference

### 3.2 Techniques Applied

- **YOLOv5 Object Detection** — Real-time vehicle detection using a quantized TFLite model
- **Non-Maximum Suppression (NMS)** — Filters duplicate bounding boxes using IoU thresholding, implemented in pure NumPy
- **Confidence Thresholding** — Filters weak detections (threshold: 0.5)
- **Bounding Box Annotation** — Draws labeled boxes on detected vehicles for visualization

### 3.3 Software Used

- Python 3.x
- `tflite-runtime` — Lightweight TFLite inference on Raspberry Pi
- `Pillow (PIL)` — Image loading, drawing, and saving
- `NumPy` — Tensor operations and custom NMS
- `Picamera2` — Camera interface for Raspberry Pi

### 3.4 Advantages of Image Processing

- Fully automated — no human operator needed for vehicle counting
- Scalable to multiple camera feeds
- Model can be updated independently of hardware

### 3.5 Challenges

- Lighting variability affects detection accuracy
- Processing latency on Raspberry Pi (~1–2s per frame without GPU)
- Occlusion in dense traffic reduces per-vehicle detection accuracy

### 3.6 Future Enhancements

- Deploy on Coral Edge TPU for 5–10× faster inference
- Add lane segmentation to track per-lane density separately
- Implement motion tracking across frames for speed estimation

